The '''Rydberg-Ritz Combination Principle''' is the theory proposed by [[Walter Ritz]] in 1908 to explain relationship of the spectral lines for all atoms.  The principle states that the [[Spectroscopy|spectral lines]] of any element include [[Frequency|frequencies]] that are either the sum or the difference of the frequencies of two other lines.

An atom can be [[Excitation|excited]] to higher [[energy]] either spontaneously or via [[absorption (electromagnetic radiation)|absorption]] of a [[photon]].  However, according to the principles of [[Quantum mechanics]], these excitations can only occur at certain energy intervals.  The Rydbergâ€“Ritz combination principle helps explain this process.

== History ==
The spectral lines of [[hydrogen]] had been analyzed and found to have a mathematical relationship in the [[Balmer series]].  This was later extended to a general formula called the [[Rydberg formula]].  This could only be applied to hydrogen-like atoms.  In 1908 Ritz derived a relationship that could be applied to all atoms.  This principle, the Rydbergâ€“Ritz combination principle, is used today in identifying the transition lines of atoms.

